<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 94 / UK Company News: Soccer's old attitudes ruled offside - Why
excluding players' values may be a commercial mistake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When Chris Sutton, Blackburn Rovers' new Pounds 5m signing, takes the field
against Southampton on the first day of the Premier League season, most fans
will probably regard him as one of the Lancashire side's prime assets.
Not so the club's accountants. Blackburn is common among English football
clubs in excluding players' values from the balance sheet.
That policy is flawed, according to accountants, Touche Ross, and
contributes to the losses which have raised serious questions about the
financial strength of the national sport.
By dealing with transfer fees through the profit and loss account, Touche
Ross believes clubs such as Blackburn are failing to show substantial asset
values in their balance sheet.
'Soccer's 'hidden assets' may put a club at a commercial disadvantage when
trying to raise finance or convey a message to investors or financial
analysts,' says Mr Gerry Boon, co-author of Touche Ross's annual survey of
football club accounts.
The survey, published today, warns that by not declaring player values in
the balance sheet, clubs fail to show an objective return on assets and
capital employed; expose themselves to large and unpredictable swings in
profits; and cannot give a realistic picture of their 'worth as a company'.
The cost to Blackburn has been high. It spent Pounds 13.1m on new players in
the 1991-92 and the 1992-93 seasons, resulting in pre-tax losses of Pounds
7.92m and Pounds 6.34m respectively.
Its spending spree helped lift the estimated value of the Premier League's
players to Pounds 250m.
Fortunately for the club, it can rely on the deep pockets of Mr Jack Walker,
the businessman who sold his steel stockholding business to British Steel
for Pounds 330m and has since acted as Blackburn's benefactor.
Most clubs do not have such backers. So why do they not embrace Touche
Ross's recommendations? The answer may be simple: tax.
By building up accumulated losses, clubs can reduce their liability to
corporation tax should they have a windfall on the sale of a star player or
on a cup run.
But such practices may soon attract the attention of the Inland Revenue,
according to Mr Colin Sandy, finance director at Tottenham Hotspur.
He believes that the Revenue's Special Compliance Office, which is currently
examining payments to players, could 'extend its inquiry to look at other
matters'.
Their attention may focus on the two thirds of clubs in the Premier League
which reported a profit in their last financial statements, but avoided
corporation tax through losses carried forward from previous years.
Newcastle United, one of the seven sides to include player values in the
balance sheet, says clubs must now face up to the challenge of introducing
efficient management.
The club changed its accounting policies after it was rescued by Sir John
Hall, the north east property entrepreneur. Mr Freddie Fletcher, chief
executive, says it was completely revamped after accountants at Cameron Hall
Developments, Sir John's private company, drew up a new financial strategy.
'This club was in a mess,' he adds.
The Football Association, however, is reluctant to endorse common accounting
standards for all clubs. Mr Mark Day, the FA's chief accountant, says there
is no proof that one accounting system is better than another. 'As long as
clubs are operating within accountancy rules, then we wouldn't seek a set
format.'
Nevertheless, Mr Boon at Touche Ross says clubs should shrug off their old
attitudes. If they don't, he warns, they may not be able to afford new
players or invest adequate sums in their stadiums.
'In order to secure the finance for such developments, clubs need to present
themselves to banks, shareholders and investors as well-managed businesses,'
he says. 'The financial manager is very much part of the squad.'
The Touche Ross Survey of Football Club Accounts. Pounds 20. PO Box 500,
Abbey House, 74 Mosley Street, Manchester M60 2AT.
