<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 94 / UK Company News: Tentative signs of financial upturn for
English football clubs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
English football is showing tentative signs of a financial upturn with most
clubs cutting their losses or moving into profit, according to accountants
Touche Ross.
The firm's annual survey of football club accounts, published today, shows
average operating profits in the Premier League more than doubled to Pounds
1.46m (Pounds 620,000) in the 1992-93 season.
Increased income from television contracts and commercial sponsors also
helped reduce average losses per club in Division One from Pounds 423,000 to
Pounds 332,000; while sides in Divisions Two and Three cut their losses from
Pounds 380,000 to Pounds 47,000 and from Pounds 140,000 to Pounds 54,000
respectively.
Although the figures represent an improvement over the previous season, the
survey shows that more than half the country's clubs continued to operate at
a loss.
Only 43 per cent of clubs were profitable at the operating level and losses
at several exceeded their total turnover.
Senior football executives also expressed concern that transfer fees - the
main source of income for most clubs - had fallen back to Pounds 73m (Pounds
75m), while almost Pounds 200m still needed to be spent improving the
country's stadiums to comply with the Taylor Report recommendations on
ground safety.
Mr Roger Alwen, chairman of Charlton Athletic - which reported losses of
Pounds 1.57m in 1992-93 compared with a Pounds 35,000 profit in the previous
year - warned that declining transfer income and refurbishment costs could
force some teams out of the Football League.
'I think there will be a fall-out of clubs in the next few years. Only
around 50 clubs may survive on a full-time basis.'
His concern was echoed by Mr Colin Sandy, finance director at Tottenham
Hotspur, which is controlled by Mr Alan Sugar. Mr Sandy warned that clubs
with insufficient gate receipts and no outside backing 'would go to the
wall'.
In the Premier League, several leading clubs incurred significant losses.
Blackburn Rovers made pre-tax losses of Pounds 6.37m (Pounds 7.93m) and
Chelsea and Wimbledon both lost more than Pounds 1m.
Touche Ross said the success of Manchester United, which made pre-tax
profits of Pounds 4.2m (Pounds 5.06m), demonstrated that clubs had to
develop commercial activities off the field in order to survive.
</TEXT>
