<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Barry Hearn is a key factor in the sports world. In the 1980s he dominated
snooker, acting as agent to most of the leading players, including Steve
Davis. When the popularity of the green baize started to wane Hearn shifted
his attention to boxing. This has proved a much harder game to crack, but,
as the manager of Chris Eubank, Hearn has already made fortunes for himself
and his clients. In On the Line: Boxing Clever (BBC 2 at 8pm), the TV
cameras follow Essex man Hearn around the world as he does his deals.
It had to happen: British television is linking into Court TV, the US
channel which brings live transmissions of court room proceedings. Tonight
there is footage of the case which has gripped the US by the throat - the
trial for murder of one of its most celebrated black sports stars and
actors, OJ Simpson. (BBC 2 at 9pm). In Travels with my Camera (Channel 4 at
9pm) Charles Nicholls tries to replicate the journey into Africa of the poet
Arthur Rimbaud a century ago.
For escapists, Martin Jarvis is reading William stories by Richmal Crompton
every morning on Radio 4 at 8.40am.
</TEXT>
