<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 94 / Lords hit at EC over visa list plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A House of Lords report published today accuses the European Commission of
exceeding its powers by seeking to impose visa requirements that narrow the
drawbridge to 'fortress Europe'.
Citizens of Commonwealth countries now entitled to make 'short-stay' visits
to the UK would be affected by a proposed regulation establishing a list of
countries whose nationals would require visas to visit any state of the
European Union.
The European communities committee calls for a 'significant pruning' of the
proposed list. This call is aimed particularly at removing Commonwealth
countries, whose citizens are more likely to go to the UK than to other
member states.
The report also advocates stronger safeguards to accompany the introduction
of a blanket ban on undesirable immigrants throughout the European Union.
Under an external frontiers convention proposed by the European Commission
all those named on a computerised joint list would be barred from all 12
member states.
The new regime would help to ensure, for example, that a person deported
from France would not be able to travel back to Frankfurt or Brussels and
then to French territory.
The committee also says that specific arrangements for airports in the
proposed convention do not take adequate account of the special position of
London as an international airport handling a great number of transit
passengers who are kept 'airside' and do not undergo passport checks.
In a recommendation which disagrees with government policy the committee
says the jurisdiction of the European Court of Justice should be extended to
settle disputes and questions arising from the proposed convention referred
to it by national tribunals.
</TEXT>
