<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 94 / Anxious wait for City on rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England's money market operations will have an unusually large
audience today as the City waits anxiously to see whether interest rates
will be raised, Philip Gawith writes.
Markets closed on Friday amid a frenzy of speculation after the Bank
accepted bids for Treasury bills - short-term government debt - at rates of
up to 5.75 per cent, half a percentage point above the level of base rates.
The move was interpreted by some traders as a sign that base rates will
shortly rise. The picture was confused, however, by the Bank dealing at
unchanged rates in its daily operations before and after the auction. The
daily activities are the customary method of indicating rate changes.
Although most weekend comment seemed to favour rates staying unchanged,
analysts said the picture was too confusing to make predictions. A decision
to raise rates would have considerable impact, affecting a range of prices
across the economy and probably having a negative impact on financial
markets.
While some recent economic data have hinted that inflationary pressures
might be developing in the economy, justifying higher rates, many economists
argue that the level of economic activity is not sufficient for a tightening
of policy.
Mr Roger Bootle, chief economist at Midland Global Markets, described
Friday's events as a chaotic situation 'which will have done the City's
reputation no end of harm'.
If rates are left unchanged, sterling could come under pressure. The UK
currency rose quite sharply on Friday, in anticipation of higher rates, and
may be vulnerable to a downward correction.
</TEXT>
