<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 94 / Companies healthier than in previous recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Industrial and commercial companies are considerably more profitable now
than at the equivalent stage in the previous recovery, Philip Gawith writes.
A study by the Bank of England has found that pre-tax return on capital in
the non-North Sea sector was 9.5 per cent in the first quarter of 1994.
This is almost double that of the equivalent stage in the previous recovery
of 1982-84, and compares to a trough of 6.3 per cent in the first quarter of
1992.
The study - by Mr Kieren Wright of the Bank's structural economic analysis
division - found that differences in profitability, investment and financial
decisions were partly attributed to the relative shallowness of the
recession.
Retained earnings increased by more than a third last year when companies
made net repayments of debt to banks equivalent to 1.8 per cent of gross
domestic product. In 1982, the comparable year in the previous cycle,
companies made net borrowings of 2.4 per cent of GDP.
The study also found companies making increasing use of capital markets for
external finance. Gross capital issues by industrial and commercial
companies rose 51 per cent to Pounds 23.9bn last year, representing 30.3 per
cent of total funding. Dividend payments continued to grow, by 9.3 per cent
to Pounds 22.7bn in 1993. Fixed investment has been higher than during
1982-84, but this reflects a higher base rather than investment rising as
the recovery has progressed.
</TEXT>
