<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 94 / Auditors face more checks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Chartered accountancy firms that conduct audits will be subject to more
frequent inspection visits under plans being drawn up by their professional
bodies.
Officials at the Joint Monitoring Unit, which scrutinises registered
auditors who are members of the UK's three chartered accountancy bodies, aim
to visit all 10,500 firms under their jurisdiction within the next five to
eight years. The action follows changes recommended in letters written
earlier this month to the regulatory bodies by Mr Neil Hamilton, minister
for corporate affairs at the Department of Trade and Industry.
It comes in a review of the first two years since the new self-regulatory
regime for auditing was established under the 1989 Companies Act.
The Joint Monitoring Unit will continue to scrutinise most closely the 160
larger firms that conduct the audits of listed and public-interest
companies, which are already scheduled to be visited once every five years.
Officials are also considering ways to change the inspection techniques of
the largest accountancy firms, in which breaches are difficult to highlight
using present approaches.
Mr Hamilton asked the bodies to:
Target firms where there was greater risk;
Ensure monitoring was linked closely to the circumstances of different
practices;
Use a wider variety of techniques to supervise the firms;
Prevent any cost increase.
They have until October to submit details of the changes.
</TEXT>
