<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 94 / Copier leasing rules amended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
New restrictions on photocopier leases are to be introduced by members of
the Finance and Leasing Association to combat criticism of the photocopier
industry by the Office of Fair Trading.
The association is proposing substantial amendments to leasing guidelines
which it hopes will overcome concerns expressed earlier this year by Sir
Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading.
Sir Bryan in March called for urgent moves to end what he described as 'an
extraordinary variety of malpractices and excesses'. He said he was prepared
to give self-regulation a chance but if that failed he would refer the
supply of photocopiers to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
Under the association's proposed guidelines, which are binding on members,
photocopier lease periods will be restricted to a maximum of five years
rather than the unspecified 'working life' of the equipment.
The association says it also intends to ensure that the controversial
cost-per-copy contracts are restricted to larger companies only, where their
use is considered to be appropriate. Sir Bryan, however, called on trade
associations actively to discourage the use of cost-per-copy arrangements.
Mr David Hardisty, association chairman, said its guidance notes on
cost-per-copy contracts seemed to be effective as it had received only one
complaint since this section came into force last year. He added: 'However,
so there is no room for doubt, we are quite happy to tighten up this area to
ensure best practice.'
</TEXT>
