<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 94 / Blair welcomes M&amp;S overture on funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair, the new Labour leader, has cautiously welcomed an invitation
from Sir Richard Greenbury, the chairman of Marks and Spencer, to discuss
whether the supermarket chain could give financial backing to the Labour
party.
Amid growing signs that leading business figures could develop contacts with
Mr Blair, M&amp;S confirmed yesterday that Sir Richard had sent the Labour
leader an invitation to hold talks.
Sir Richard's move coincided with reports that Mr David Sainsbury, the
millionaire supermarket chief, financially backed Mr Blair's campaign for
the Labour leadership.
In recent years M&amp;S has invited Mr Blair's predecessors Mr Neil Kinnock and
the late John Smith to discuss policy issues and the prospect of financial
backing.
Both men declined these invitations.
But there were indications yesterday that Mr Blair, who has spearheaded a
drive to modernise Labour, could break with previous practice. 'If the
chairman of Marks and Spencer wants to discuss matters of mutual interest,
then it would be churlish not to agree,' said Labour.
M&amp;S said that Sir Richard would want to hear what policies Labour had that
might affect retailing. 'If they were of benefit, the main board would
discuss finance (for the Labour party),' it said.
In its 1993 annual report M&amp;S revealed a donation of Pounds 40,000 to
Conservative Central Office. The company said yesterday that 'whatever
happened, we would continue to support the Conservative party'. But it added
that supporting both Labour and the Tories would not be a problem in
principle.
Labour officials underlined that Mr Blair could not be expected to tailor
policies in exchange for financial backing.
They would not confirm that Mr Sainsbury, who backed the formation of the
Social Democratic party in the early 1980s, had donated Pounds 5,000 to Mr
Blair's leadership campaign.
</TEXT>
