<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 94 / Student loans may be sold off to cut education spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Government is considering privatising the Student Loans Company in
response to the prospect of a further Treasury squeeze on higher education
funding.
Ministers are studying two options for the organisation responsible for
administering loans to students in higher education: an outright
privatisation, probably via a sale to a group of banks; or, more probably,
securitising the company's debt.
Both would be designed to cut dramatically the up-front cost of the loan
operation, which on present plans will rise to Pounds 688m next year and
Pounds 900m in 1996-97.
The government plans to increase the proportion of students' living costs
funded by repayable loans by 10 per cent for each of the next three years
and to impose parallel cuts in student grant rates.
But the rapid rise in the number of students going into higher education and
the lengthy terms of repayment of the loans means that the finances of the
Student Loans Company, at present a government agency, will remain in
deficit for at least 10 years.
Former students do not begin repaying the loans until they have reached an
income threshold of 85 per cent of average earnings and the repayment rate
is pegged solely to the retail price index. So far more than a million loans
have been taken out. Treasury demands for a reduction in overall government
spending limits have put the Education Department under pressure to reduce
its higher education budget.
One option is to repeat the decision taken in the 1993 Budget to cap tuition
fees paid to the universities, removing the incentive for them to expand
departments and take on extra students. But in political terms removing the
cost of loans from the government's books would be a much more attractive
route.
In 1989 the main clearing banks rejected a government scheme under which
they would have administered the loans. But ministers believe the absence of
the feared political backlash against the loan system and the small
proportion of loan defaults might persuade financial institutions to rethink
their opposition.
Outright privatisation, however, would require legislation, deferring any
savings at least until 1996.
Securitisation of the debt - its sale to financial institutions at a
discount or with a Treasury guarantee - would also remove the cost from the
Treasury's books and could be done without legislation.
Such a move would be in line with the announcement last week by Mr John
Major, the prime minister, that all public expenditure demands should in
future be tested against the possibility of a privately financed
alternative.
Samuel Brittan, Page 14
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
