<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 94 / World Commodities Prices: Wool
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Opening auctions of the new selling season in Australia brought a fresh rise
in wool prices this week, which continued and led to an increase in the
newly based market indicator of 7 cents, to close at 681 cents a kg. This
means an increase compared with the end of June of about 15 cents or 2.5%,
though adjustments make exact comparisons difficult. Wool at other auctions
this week, in New Zealand and of British wool in Bradford, showed a similar
or greater advance. Traders still indicate resistance to higher prices from
the retail end, despite the maintained upward trend and the relatively low
level of wool prices on any long term comparison. Holidays now affect many
of the leading wool processing countries in Europe but otherwise activity is
good.
